-- PRESS DIGEST - Bulgaria - Sept 10
-- 
-- Wed Sep 10, 2014 02:57AM EDT
-- None



SOFIA, Sept 10 (Reuters) - These are some of the main stories in Bulgarian newspapers on Wednesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

-- Troubled Corporate Commercial Bank (Corpbank) <6C9.BB> could remain shut down for another 40 days, the central bank said (Trud, Standart). -- Russian-French businessman and activist Nicolai Koblyakov,  a prominent opponent of Russian President Vladimir Putin who was detained at the Sofia airport in July, was released on recognizance, the Sofia City Court said.  Koblyakov, wanted by Russia on suspicion of fraud between 2004 and 2005, was freed from custody a few days after being detained and was placed under house arrest a month later (Trud, Standart, Presa). CAPITAL DAILY - Bulgarian Energy Holdinh (BEH), the parent of indebted state-owned power company NEK and other state energy companies, increased its capital by 336 million levs (222.40 million US dollar) to 2.9 billion levs, the company said.  -- Interim Environment Minister Svetlana Zhekova has issued a ban on the use of unconventional gas exploration and production technologies at license block Vranino in northeastern Bulgaria. The environment ministry's decision on gas exploration in the area was met with strong civil discontent and protests (Trud, Standart).